ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[Norwalk-like viruses are typically associated with outbreaks of
self-limited gastroenteritis with symptoms that may include nausea,
diarrhea, vomiting, abdominal cramping, fever, and malaise. Outbreaks
are characteristically associated with contaminated water supplies and
food-borne outbreaks are frequent. Contaminated shellfish are major
causes of epidemic gastroenteritis, with bivalve molluscs (oyster,
mussels, and cockles) being the most common source. These animals
are filter-feeders and can become infected where there is discharge of
raw sewage. This is the likely source of the virus in the present
instance, rather than the outbreaks of "winter-vomiting" illness
common in northern Europe at this time of year, which appear to be
maintained by person-to-person transmission. Readers are referred to
previous posts on ProMED-mail for further discussion of this topic.
- Mod.CP
....................mpp/cp/pg/jw
